(
<figureCitation box="[602,724,472,497]" captionStart-0="Figs 42–44" captionStart-1="Figs 45–51" captionStartId-0="10.[133,170,1643,1662]" captionStartId-1="11.[133,170,1621,1640]" captionTargetBox-0="[137,1156,814,1590]" captionTargetBox-1="[137,1151,220,1593]" captionTargetId-1="figure-58@11.[640,1145,777,1051]" captionTargetPageId-0="10" captionTargetPageId-1="11" captionText-0="Figs 42–44. Megaselia miroparaphysis n. sp. male: 42 – frons; 43 – postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 44 – left face of thorax." captionText-1="Figs 45–51. Megaselia miroparaphysis n. sp. male: 45 – scutellum; 46–48 – hypopygium; 49 – front tarsus; 50 – hind femur and tibia; 51 – wing." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252171" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252175" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6252171/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6252175/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Figs 42–51</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[133,1154,519,788]" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">
Diagnosis (male). In the keys to British species (
<bibRefCitation author="DISNEY R. H. L." box="[732,875,519,543]" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref7257" refString="DISNEY R. H. L. 1989. Scuttle Flies Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects 10 (8): 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplets 80 or 87, but its hypopygium differs from the species of these couplets and subsequently described species, as well as by other details. The hypopygium of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lundbeck)" baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[765,1059,580,604]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigripalpis">
<emphasis box="[765,923,580,604]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">M. nigripalpis</emphasis>
(Lundbeck)
</taxonomicName>
was not illustrated but (as its name indicates) it has dark palps. In the keys of Schmitz &amp; Beyer (1965) it runs to couplet 15 on page 521 to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lundbeck)" baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[645,959,642,666]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sepulchralis">
<emphasis box="[645,818,642,666]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">M. sepulchralis</emphasis>
(Lundbeck)
</taxonomicName>
, which differs in having dark palps, legs and the anal tube of its different hypopygium. With its costal index of 0.44 the new species also needs to be run through the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="SCHMITZ H. &amp; DELAGE A." box="[859,1149,703,727]" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" pagination="638 - 664" refId="ref7540" refString="SCHMITZ H. &amp; DELAGE A. 1974. Phoridae. In: LINDNER E. (ed.), Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region 4 (33) (Lieferung 301): 638 - 664. Stuttgart, E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung." type="book chapter" year="1974">Schmitz &amp; Delage (1974)</bibRefCitation>
, where it runs to couplets 32 and 36 on page 640. Its hypopygium differs from the species of these couplets.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252171" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6252171" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252171/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" startId="10.[133,170,1643,1662]" targetBox="[137,1156,814,1590]" targetPageId="10">
<paragraph blockId="10.[133,1154,1643,1687]" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">
Figs 42–44. 
<taxonomicName authority="DISNEY &amp; WINQVIST, 2018" authorityName="DISNEY &amp; WINQVIST" authorityYear="2018" box="[240,468,1643,1662]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miroparaphysis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[240,468,1643,1662]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="21">Megaselia miroparaphysis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[474,521,1644,1663]" pageId="10" pageNumber="21" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
male: 42 – frons; 43 – postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 44 – left face of thorax.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252175" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6252175" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252175/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="22" startId="11.[133,170,1621,1640]" targetBox="[137,1151,220,1593]" targetPageId="11">
<paragraph blockId="11.[133,1155,1621,1665]" pageId="11" pageNumber="22">
Figs 45–51. 
<taxonomicName authority="DISNEY &amp; WINQVIST, 2018" authorityName="DISNEY &amp; WINQVIST" authorityYear="2018" box="[241,470,1621,1640]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miroparaphysis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[241,470,1621,1640]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="22">Megaselia miroparaphysis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[476,524,1622,1641]" pageId="11" pageNumber="22" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
male: 45 – scutellum; 46–48 – hypopygium; 49 – front tarsus; 50 – hind femur and tibia; 51 – wing.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="12.[133,1154,226,710]" pageId="12" pageNumber="23">
Male. Frons as 
<figureCitation box="[353,430,226,250]" captionStart="Figs 42–44" captionStartId="10.[133,170,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[137,1156,814,1590]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 42–44. Megaselia miroparaphysis n. sp. male: 42 – frons; 43 – postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 44 – left face of thorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252171" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252171/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="23">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
and with dense but very fine microtrichia. Postpedicels, palps and proboscis as 
<figureCitation box="[277,358,256,280]" captionStart="Figs 42–44" captionStartId="10.[133,170,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[137,1156,814,1590]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 42–44. Megaselia miroparaphysis n. sp. male: 42 – frons; 43 – postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 44 – left face of thorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252171" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252171/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="23">Fig. 43</figureCitation>
, the postpedicels being without SPS vesicles. Thorax brown, with three notopleural bristles and no cleft in front of these, and mesopleuron with hairs (
<figureCitation box="[1055,1142,287,311]" captionStart="Figs 42–44" captionStartId="10.[133,170,1643,1662]" captionTargetBox="[137,1156,814,1590]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 42–44. Megaselia miroparaphysis n. sp. male: 42 – frons; 43 – postpedicels, palps and proboscis; 44 – left face of thorax." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252171" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252171/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="23">Fig. 44</figureCitation>
). Scutellum with an anterior pair of hairs, a posterior pair of bristles and a posterior pair of hairs (
<figureCitation box="[141,224,348,372]" captionStart="Figs 45–51" captionStartId="11.[133,170,1621,1640]" captionTargetBox="[137,1151,220,1593]" captionTargetId="figure-58@11.[640,1145,777,1051]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 45–51. Megaselia miroparaphysis n. sp. male: 45 – scutellum; 46–48 – hypopygium; 49 – front tarsus; 50 – hind femur and tibia; 51 – wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252175" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252175/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="23">Fig. 45</figureCitation>
). Abdominal tergites brown with hairs mainly at hind margins. Venter gray, and with hairs on segments 3–6. Hypopygium as 
<figureCitation box="[565,689,379,403]" captionStart="Figs 45–51" captionStartId="11.[133,170,1621,1640]" captionTargetBox="[137,1151,220,1593]" captionTargetId="figure-58@11.[640,1145,777,1051]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 45–51. Megaselia miroparaphysis n. sp. male: 45 – scutellum; 46–48 – hypopygium; 49 – front tarsus; 50 – hind femur and tibia; 51 – wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252175" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252175/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="23">Figs 46–48</figureCitation>
. Middle and hind legs brown but front legs yellowish brown or paler in part. Fore tarsus as 
<figureCitation box="[686,770,410,434]" captionStart="Figs 45–51" captionStartId="11.[133,170,1621,1640]" captionTargetBox="[137,1151,220,1593]" captionTargetId="figure-58@11.[640,1145,777,1051]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 45–51. Megaselia miroparaphysis n. sp. male: 45 – scutellum; 46–48 – hypopygium; 49 – front tarsus; 50 – hind femur and tibia; 51 – wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252175" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252175/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="23">Fig. 49</figureCitation>
. Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends about 0.6 times its length. Hind femur and tibia as 
<figureCitation box="[823,906,440,464]" captionStart="Figs 45–51" captionStartId="11.[133,170,1621,1640]" captionTargetBox="[137,1151,220,1593]" captionTargetId="figure-58@11.[640,1145,777,1051]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 45–51. Megaselia miroparaphysis n. sp. male: 45 – scutellum; 46–48 – hypopygium; 49 – front tarsus; 50 – hind femur and tibia; 51 – wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252175" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252175/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="23">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
, the tibia with 14–15 differentiated posterodorsal hairs, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (
<figureCitation box="[221,301,502,526]" captionStart="Figs 45–51" captionStartId="11.[133,170,1621,1640]" captionTargetBox="[137,1151,220,1593]" captionTargetId="figure-58@11.[640,1145,777,1051]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 45–51. Megaselia miroparaphysis n. sp. male: 45 – scutellum; 46–48 – hypopygium; 49 – front tarsus; 50 – hind femur and tibia; 51 – wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6252175" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6252175/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="23">Fig. 51</figureCitation>
) 2.0 mm long. Costal index 0.44. Costal ratios 3.9: 2.4: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity box="[244,340,532,556]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="12" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.16">0.16 mm</quantity>
long. A small hair at base of vein 3. With 3 axillary bristles, the outer being 
<quantity box="[133,228,563,587]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="12" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.14">0.14 mm</quantity>
long. Sc not reaching R1. Haltere brown.
</paragraph>
